Saturday 9 November

President Trump Impeachment Inquiry

National security European advisor testifies against president trump

The facts of the story:

  • The transcript of Lt Col Alexander Vindmans testimony is released, in which he says there was no doubt that President Trump expected a public investigation into Joe Bidens son, from the President of Ukraine. In return, President Trump would release the $400 million in military aid he has stalled.
  • Lt Col Vindman, who serves as the director for European affairs on the National Security Council, sat in on the phone call, which is now the subject of an impeachment inquiry.
  • At the time, Lt Col Vindman wrote a memo recommending that the military aid be released, although this was not acted upon.

UK general election

what is in the withdrawal agreement?

The Withdrawal Agreement is the most important part of the Brexit negotiations - it details how Britain will exit the EU.

Conservatives want to leave the EU with this deal.

Labour wants to renegotiate, what they see as a better deal, then put it to a public referendum.

Northern Ireland

The bill provides for customs checks on goods being moved between Britain and Northern Ireland in order to avoid a hard border on the island.

This latest deal sees Northern Ireland leave the EU's customs union, but remain partially aligned to the single market. It will remain in the UK's customs territory and follow EU procedures for goods arriving into the country.

The EU procedures will include legislation on goods; sanitary rules for veterinary controls (SPS rules); rules on agricultural production/marketing; VAT and excise in respect of goods; and state aid rules.

No EU tariffs would be paid on personal goods and good for immediate consumption carried by travellers across the Irish border rather than subsequent processing.

Environmental Rights

The Protocol includes a commitment to continue to respect environmental principles. It aims to ensure the level of environmental protection provided by law, regulations and practices is not reduced below the level provided by the common standards applicable within the Union and the UK at the end of the transition period.

The Protocol enables the Joint Committee (the body that will deal with EU-UK matters during the transition period) to lay down minimum commitments that will apply after the end of the transition period for reducing national emissions of certain atmospheric pollutants, for the maximum sulphur content of marine fuels and for best available techniques and emission levels for industrial emissions. The UK also commits to introducing a carbon pricing system of at least the same effectiveness and scope as the EU Emissions Trading System.

Citizen Rights

EU nationals in the UK and Britons in the EU plus family members would retain residency and social security rights after Brexit. Freedom to move and live within the EU and UK would continue during the transition period. People would be allowed to stay when it ends and apply for permanent residence after five years.

The right for British citizens settled in an EU country to move freely after Brexit within the EU as they can now remains subject to a future agreement.

Workers Rights

The UK will abide by EU standards on workers rights and the environment, but these commitments have been shifted to the forward-looking political declaration, as opposed to being enshrined in law.

It will be up to the government that negotiates the free trade deal to decide how strong a commitment to EU rules, including workers rights, it is prepared to make.

Trade

The new document relates to a future EU-UK economic relationship where the UK opts for a Free Trade Agreement (FTA). But in return for zero tariffs and quotas, the UK makes "robust commitments on a level playing field" to ensure "open and fair competition". The new political declaration is causing concern among some Brexit opponents especially given the Johnson government's avowed intention to diverge from EU rules and forge an independent trading path.

Other

The issue of fishing rights is left to be dealt with on another day. The agreement says the EU and UK should do their best to strike a separate deal on access to UK waters for EU fishing boats.


They will also require the Government to monitor new EU legislation covering employment and workplace health and safety standards after the transition period. It will report on these changes and the Governments intended course of action on a regular basis to Parliament.


World News

UN is gravely concerned following escalation of violence in Iraq.

The Facts today:

  • Since the start of last month, over 300 people have died in protests in Iraq.
  • There have been claims that the army has used live ammunition, as opposed to the standard rubber bullets, against protesters in the last 24 hours.
  • This came after government promises to halt the use of live ammunition.
  • At least a dozen have died in the last 24 hours as protests escalated.
  • The Human Rights Watch reported the use of tear gas against protesters.
  • UN Human Rights Office tweet: We are gravely concerned about continuing reports of deaths & injuries resulting from the use of force against demonstrators, as well as deliberate killings. We call on the authorities to take firm steps for dialogue. We stand ready to assist.

Friday 8 November

UK News

All 39 people that were found dead in Essex have been identified.

The Facts today:

  • Assistant Chief Constable Tim Smith has said that all of the 39 people that were found dead in a trailer in Essex have been identified.
  • All of the 39 that died are Vietnamese. 31 are men, 8 are women.
  • The identities have not been released, as the police want to notify the families of the victims first arrested 11 people.
  • Vietnamese authorities have arrested 8 people in relation to the matter. 2 people have been charged in the UK, Maurice Robinson and Eamonn Harrison from Northern Ireland.

Irish man released without charge following 15 found in lorry

The Facts today:

  • The British Home Office has confirmed that 15 people have been found in the back of a lorry late on Wednesday evening, after an Irish truck driver heard a knocking in the lorry, and pulled over after assuming a flat tire.
  • The 15 identified themselves as being from Iran and Iraq.
  • The lorry driver was arrested at the scene but released at about 7PM Thursday.
  • All 15 have been taken into custody on suspicion of immigration offences. One of the people found was taken to hospital as a precaution, but then released later in the day.

Climate change

Almost complete approval from parliament for New Zealand zero carbon law in Parliament.

The Facts today:

  • A new bill that passed through Parliament in New Zealand has committed the government to keep the effects of climate change to a global temperature increase of less than 1.5C above the pre-Industrial level.
  • Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern gave a speech before voting on the bill will make the aim for New Zealand to be almost carbon neutral by 2050 a law in the country.
  • The energy grid will aim to be run completely on renewables by 2035.
  • Carbon budgets will be produced every 5 years to stipulate the amount of carbon the government will be permitted to emit.
  • The leader of the largest opposition party, Simon Bridges, before confirming his parties support for the bill said: Compromise shouldnt be a dirty word in politics.

Thursday 7 November

World news

37 killed in Burkina Faso after an attack on a convoy from a Canadian mining company.

The Facts today:

  • A regional governor has said that at least 37 have died and at least 40 have been injured following an attack on a Canadian mining convoy from gunmen.
  • Semafo, the mining company, operates two gold mines in the region, following previous attacks on the mines, all expatriate employees travel by helicopter between the mines.
  • The last few years have seen an unprecedented rise in attacks in northern Burkina Faso from jihadists, in what was a peaceful nation.

UK general election

Labour deputy leader Tom Watson steps down.

The Facts today:

  • The deputy leader of the Labour party Tom Watson has stepped down from his role and will not be standing in the December 12 General Election.
  • He cited personal reasons for not running again and has said he will be supporting Labour through the run up to the election.
  • Over the past few months, he has called for Labour to be a pro-Remain party. The party leader Jeremy Corbyn insists that people on both sides of the Brexit debate should be represented by the Labour party.

Misleading statements in Liberal Democrats Advertising.

The Facts today:

  • In an election leaflet, the Liberal Democrats quote The Guardian newspaper as saying Lib Dems winning and on the up after by-election victory.
  • The quote is actually from the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Jo Swinson, which was then reported by The Guardian.
  • A bar chart was also shown on a Liberal Democrat leaflet that claimed that it represented data from European elections, although it didnt provide a source, an axis, or an explanation for the data represented in the chart.

President Trump Impeachment Inquiry

Supported statement from former US Ambassador to Ukraine implicates President Trump with Quid Pro Quo

The Facts today:

  • A testimony given by former Ukraine ambassador Bill Taylor on 22 October was released yesterday.
  • The statement he gave has been supported by nearly a dozen other witnesses
  • The testimony described two state department officials as saying Trump would not sign a check for military aid until the Ukrainian president went to a microphone and say he is opening investigations of Biden and 2016 election interference.
  • Public impeachment proceedings are to begin on Wednesday.
  • President Trump is facing possible impeachment for suggesting to the Ukrainian Prime Minister that he should investigate Joe Bidens son, Hunter, for baseless rumours that Joe Biden stopped an investigation into a Ukrainian company Hunter worked at. This came as military aid to Ukraine was paused.

Wednesday 6 November

World news

Steps towards peace in Yemen as separatists and government sign a peace deal.

The Facts today:

  • A power struggle in southern Yemen has been brought to an end following a peace deal between the Yemen government and southern separatists.
  • This is one part of a conflict in Yemen that has raged since 2015. The conflict has killed over 7,000 people, and an estimated 50,000 people have died due to the famine caused by the war.
  • The separatists will now become part of the official Yemen government, and their armed forces will come under the control of the government.
  • The two sides previously fought together against the Houthis(an Islamic group, that sees itself as the official Yemen government) that occupies land in the north of the country.


From around the Web:

Nigerian police free 259 people from an Islamic institution.

The Facts today:

  • Nigerian police free 259 people, mostly men and boys from an Islamic institution. 9 people were arrested.
  • The people, some of whom had been held in the institution for years, were given only one meal a day, and some of the victims had been physically and sexually abused.
  • In the past month, Nigerian police have released over 1000 people from these institutions.
  • Some people in the region send relatives to these institutions to be rehabilitated following petty crimes and other perceived problems.

UK general election

Read the Withdrawal Agreement here

Jeremy Corbyn clarifies Labour policy on Brexit.

The Facts today:

  • Labour leader Jeremy Corbyn has officially declared the Brexit policy of the Labour Party for the December 12 general election.
  • If elected, the party will aim to renegotiate PM Boris Johnsons Withdrawal Agreement with the EU. They will look for amendments such as workers and environmental protections.
  • This would then be put to a public referendum, with the aim for a Summer 2020 date.
  • The referendum will ask to either leave the EU with the Labour Withdrawal Agreement or else to remain in the EU.


  • The policy of the Conservative Party is to leave the EU with the current Withdrawal Agreement.
  • The policy of the Liberal Democrats is to remain inside the EU.


Jacob Rees-Mogg draws criticism after statement on Grenfell Tower.

The Facts today:

  • "The more one's read over the weekend about the report and about the chances of people surviving, if you just ignore what you're told and leave you are so much safer.
  • "And I think if either of us were in a fire, whatever the fire brigade said, we would leave the burning building. It just seems the common sense thing to do.
  • "And it is such a tragedy that that didn't happen."
  • The advice is designed to prevent hundreds of people descending stairs while firefighters are coming up during a contained fire.
  • He issued an apology on Tuesday saying: What I meant to say is that I would have also listened to the fire brigades advice to stay and wait at the time.


  • However, with what we know now and with hindsight I wouldnt, and I dont think anyone else would.
  • 72 people died in the 2017 fire in an apartment block
  • After a review of the tragedy, the London Fire Brigade Commissioner said that after what they now know about buildings with the type of cladding that Grenfell Tower had, things would be done differently.
